awd_titl_txt: Teaming Engineering and Mathematics Students for the Future
awd_abstract_narration:
Increasing enrollments in STEM should reflect the nation's diversity. This creates a compelling need to ensure access and support to economically-disadvantaged and first generation students pursuing STEM careers. It is imperative to understand which interventions most effectively support these students. This project will award 100 scholarships over five years to first year and transfer students entering West Texas A&M University (WTAMU) as engineering or mathematics students. It is designed to promote and ensure the retention and graduation of engineering and mathematics students from three underrepresented and/or disadvantaged populations: (1) rural, economically-disadvantaged students; (2) minority students; and (3) first-generation college students at this Hispanic Serving Institution. This project will compare the benefit of financial support alone to the benefit of receiving support that includes financial assistance as well as academic, social, and career support. The project will also identify the modifications to traditional learning communities and Peer-Led Team Learning (PLTL) models required to address the challenges facing underrepresented students in STEM. 

The goal of this project is to develop well-trained professionals who are ready to contribute to the economic growth and competitiveness of the nation's work force. The project has three objectives: (1) increase the recruitment, retention, student success, and graduation of low-income, academically talented students pursuing degrees in STEM fields; (2) adapt, implement, and study models of effective evidence-based practices, and strategies that contribute to understanding of how these practices affect recruitment, retention, and student success; and (3) contribute to the implementation of co-curricular PLTL and Experiential Learning activities. The project will recruit academically talented students from regional high schools and partnering community colleges with large minority and economically disadvantaged populations. Scholarships will reduce or eliminate the need for students to seek employment while pursuing their degrees.  The program will establish learning communities and block scheduling for students with similar educational trajectories. The communities will be involved in peer-led team learning, experiential learning, workforce exposure, and career counseling to foster social and academic success. This will further enhance the likelihood of persistence in STEM and STEM careers. The interaction of student cohorts will encourage the exchange of ideas. It will also foster appreciation of the interdependence and interdisciplinary nature of the sciences. Results from the project will provide a model for higher education providers in states across the nation experiencing growth in the Hispanic population and other underrepresented groups to recruit, retain, and increase degree attainment of undergraduate students in STEM fields.

por.por_cntn:
The West Texas A&M University (WTAMU) Teaming Engineering and Mathematics Students for the Future (TEAMSF) S-STEM Track-2 program was designed to ensure the retention and graduation of  engineering and mathematics students representing three underrepresented and/or disadvantaged populations including a) rural, economically-disadvantaged students b) minority, predominantly Hispanic students, and c) first-generation college students.

The project has increased awareness of NSF scholarship opportunities among high school students, leading to a higher number of applicants for engineering and mathematics programs. The outreach efforts has resulted in a diversified applicant pool, particularly from underrepresented groups (benefiting the rapidly- expanding Hispanic student population) in STEM fields. Over the past four years, the College of Engineering (COE) has actively reached out to Canyon High School, Randall High School, and West Plains High School to recruit students into our programs. Faculty and staff have engaged with these schools and hosted activities at the College to welcome prospective students. The enrollment trends for the College of Engineering over the last four years can be found below.

Financial support from scholarships enabled students to focus on their studies, potentially leading to higher retention and graduation rates in these fields. TEAMSF has supported a minimum of least 14 and maximum of 28 new and continuing scholarships every year for entering freshmen or transfer students, to address unmet financial need and reduce or eliminate the need for students to seek part-time or full-time employment. The TEAMSF program has awarded scholarships of $ 694,228 to 72 students (49 % of whom are women and 54% Hispanic) and have a 68% graduation rate as of Fall 2024. 25% of TEAMSF participants are still in the program or have graduated and are continuing STEM education or are currently working in a STEM field. More than half of the TEAMSF Scholars were first-generation students. One of the standout achievements of the TEAMSF program is our success in recruiting, retaining, and graduating women and minority students in engineering and mathematics. This has been accomplished through the creation of learning communities in first-year mathematics courses and the early introduction of peer-to-peer mentoring, via Peer-Led Team Learning (PLTL), as well as industry-to-student mentoring.

The TEAMSF cohort model has fostered a supportive academic community, enhancing collaboration, peer support, and academic success, which improved student engagement and retention. The COE established learning community groups in entry-level courses to provide academic and social support. TEAMSF scholars were advised to join these groups, allowing same-year scholarship recipients to be concurrently enrolled in engineering and mathematics courses. This approach helped TEAMSF students build a strong network, supporting each other academically and in extracurricular activities within and outside of STEM. In fall 2023, the COE moved to a specific student-advisor assignment model, where each faculty advisor is assigned 10 to 20 students. This system offers personalized guidance, better accountability, and data-driven decisions to enhance student success.

Increased student engagement and understanding of mathematics concepts through PLTL. Enhanced retention and academic performance of TEAMSF scholars due to peer support and additional academic resources, leading to improved outcomes in STEM courses. The program organically developed to include a form of PLTL, which encouraged students to seek help from peers rather than relying on tutoring centers or faculty members. This approach was instrumental in building strong relationships within engineering and mathematics, which significantly influenced their determination to overcome challenges and persist in their degree programs.

Students gained practical experience and professional connections, better preparing them for STEM careers. Experiential learning opportunities have strengthened their resumes and increased employability. Numerous cohort-building activities, including expert visits and events hosted by project leadership, have fostered valuable relationships among students. Additional supports, such as workforce exposure and career counseling, have increased the likelihood of students remaining in STEM and pursuing STEM careers. The TEAMSF program has supported underrepresented and disadvantaged students while generating insights into the value of these supports for achieving desired outcomes at WTAMU and similar universities.

Collecting comparative data between TEAMSF scholars and non-TEAMSF students has enabled a more accurate assessment of the program's impact. Matched peer groups identified the unique benefits of the TEAMSF program. Propensity score analysis was used to match TEAMSF scholars from fall cohorts 2017–2022 with a historical comparison group. The study shows that TEAMSF scholars graduate at a higher rate, nearing statistical significance, within the three-year timeframe.

We have widely shared our program results through publications, contributing to a broader understanding of effective STEM student support. The best practices we develop will benefit our university and can also serve as a model for other institutions aiming to enhance their support for STEM students.
